---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  pageHeading="Residential Solar Setups"
  description="Everyone told me I needed 50W of solar and a 40-foot tower. I've been running 10W on a 15-foot flagpole for months. Here's what actually works."
>
  <!-- Intro -->
  <section class="prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
    <h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-tight text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">
      Residential solar setups that actually work
    </h2>
    <p class="text-xl text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
      The mesh networking forums are full of people who'll tell you that you need a 40-foot tower and 50W of solar or don't bother. That's nonsense.
    </p>
    <p class="text-xl text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
      I've been running Router 1 on 10W of solar from a 15-foot flagpole in my backyard for months. It works. Here's how I did it, and how you can too.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The Anti-Dogma Manifesto -->
  <section class="mt-12 rounded-3xl border-2 border-kc-red/30 bg-gradient-to-br from-kc-red/5 to-sunset-amber/5 p-6 sm:p-8 dark:border-sunset-amber/20 dark:from-kc-red/10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-kc-red dark:text-sunset-amber">The perfectionism problem</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>Online mesh communities have a perfectionism problem.</strong> People obsess over optimal configurations instead of just deploying something that works.
      </p>
      <p>
        "You need 50W of solar for reliability." — No you don't. 10W handles Midwest weather fine.<br />
        "Indoor nodes are useless." — Wrong. <strong>Router 1 runs indoors</strong> on my top floor next to an outward-facing wall. Gets 5 miles of coverage. Test your building.<br />
        "Must have vertical polarization." — Horizontal works with trade-offs.<br />
        "HOAs make it impossible." — Flagpoles, decorative posts, attic installations—there are ways.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Deployed imperfect beats theoretical perfect.</strong> Get a node up and optimize later if needed.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Power Reality Check -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">The actual power requirements</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        A Meshtastic router consumes about 2-3 watt-hours per day. That's tiny. Even in winter with short days, 10W of solar is enough.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-200 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-800">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-kc-blue dark:text-kc-sky">What you actually need</h3>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <li>• 10W solar panel ($15-25)</li>
          <li>• 10Ah LiFePO4 battery ($20-30)</li>
          <li>• Simple charge controller ($5-10)</li>
          <li>• Router draws ~100-150mA average</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-200 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-800">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-kc-blue dark:text-kc-sky">What forums tell you to buy</h3>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <li>• 50W solar panel ($60-100)</li>
          <li>• 20Ah AGM battery ($50-80)</li>
          <li>• MPPT charge controller ($30-50)</li>
          <li>• "For reliability" (unnecessary)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 rounded-xl bg-mesh-green/10 border border-mesh-green/30 p-5">
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
        <strong>My actual setup:</strong> 10W panel, 10Ah LiFePO4, built-in charge controller. Total cost ~$50. <strong>Router and MQTT gateway both run indoors</strong> on top floor next to outward-facing wall. Has survived Kansas City winter with days of cloud cover. Still running, still covering 5+ miles.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Stealth Deployment Strategies -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">HOA-friendly deployment strategies</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>HOAs are a common excuse for not deploying.</strong> Here are four ways I've seen people work around restrictions.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 space-y-6">
      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Strategy 1: Flagpole Integration</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>What it is:</strong> Mount hardware inside or at base of decorative flagpole. Most HOAs allow flagpoles. Federal law (Freedom to Display the American Flag Act) protects your right to fly the flag.</p>
          <p><strong>How I did it:</strong> 15-foot aluminum flagpole ($40 on Amazon). Antenna hidden inside top section. Electronics in waterproof box at base. Small solar panel either disguised as decorative element or positioned discretely.</p>
          <p><strong>Cost:</strong> $100-150 total including flagpole</p>
          <p><strong>Height achieved:</strong> 15 feet (good enough for 5+ miles)</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Strategy 2: Fence Post Extension</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>What it is:</strong> Extend existing fence post or add "decorative" post to backyard fence. Frame as landscape improvement, not radio installation.</p>
          <p><strong>How to do it:</strong> 4x4 post extension bringing fence height to 8-10 feet. Mount small enclosure designed to look like post cap or birdhouse. Solar panel angled as "decorative metal art" or similar.</p>
          <p><strong>Cost:</strong> $75-125 depending on post and disguise quality</p>
          <p><strong>Height achieved:</strong> 8-10 feet (still useful, better than nothing)</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Strategy 3: Indoor Installation</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>What it is:</strong> Install node indoors on top floor near outward-facing wall or window. Completely invisible. <strong>This is literally what I'm running for Router 1.</strong></p>
          <p><strong>Testing required:</strong> Put a cheap node indoors first and test signal strength. Wood frame construction works well. Brick/stone/metal attenuates more. You won't know until you test your building.</p>
          <p><strong>Cost:</strong> $30-50 (just the node, no solar needed—run off wall power)</p>
          <p><strong>Performance:</strong> Router 1 gets 5+ miles from my top floor next to outward-facing wall. Attic installations vary (1-3 miles typical).</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-ink-600 dark:text-cream-200"><strong>Reality check:</strong> Would outdoor be better? Absolutely. But indoor deployment is not the end of the world. Get something up and running, optimize later if you want.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Strategy 4: Maximum Stealth (Birdhouse Disguise)</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>What it is:</strong> Build or buy large decorative birdhouse. Mount on shepherd's hook, post, or tree at property edge. Hide all electronics inside.</p>
          <p><strong>How to do it:</strong> Large birdhouse ($20-40) with waterproof modifications. Small omnidirectional antenna looks like mounting peg. Tiny solar panel on "roof" painted to match or disguised as decorative shingle.</p>
          <p><strong>Cost:</strong> $100-150 including birdhouse, modifications, hardware</p>
          <p><strong>Height achieved:</strong> 6-10 feet depending on mount</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-ink-600 dark:text-cream-200">This is absurd. I love it. Someone in the KC mesh should build one and report back.</p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Elevation Reality -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">How much height do you actually need?</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>Forums say: "Need 40-foot tower minimum for serious coverage."</strong><br />
        <strong>Reality: 15 feet works fine for most residential deployments.</strong>
      </p>
      <p>
        More height is better, yes. But the difference between 15 feet and 40 feet isn't as dramatic as people claim, especially in flat Kansas City terrain. The main thing is clearing immediate obstacles (neighboring houses, trees, fences).
      </p>
      <p>
        My Router 1 at 15 feet above ground reaches 5-8 miles. That's useful. That's functional. That's deployed infrastructure instead of theoretical perfection.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">
      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-kc-blue dark:text-kc-sky">6-10 ft</div>
        <div class="mt-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Minimum useful height</div>
        <div class="mt-1 text-xs text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">1-3 miles typical. Better than nothing. Start here if HOA-restricted.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-mesh-green">15-20 ft</div>
        <div class="mt-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Sweet spot for residential</div>
        <div class="mt-1 text-xs text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">5-8 miles achievable. Flagpole height. Good cost/benefit.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-prairie-gold">40+ ft</div>
        <div class="mt-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Great if you can get it</div>
        <div class="mt-1 text-xs text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">10-20+ miles possible. Requires tower/repeater site. Not residential-achievable for most.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Bill of Materials -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">What it actually costs</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        Three tiers depending on your situation and budget. All prices are approximate and based on what I've actually paid or seen others pay.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 space-y-6">
      <div class="rounded-3xl border-2 border-kc-blue/30 bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-kc-blue/20 dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-kc-blue dark:text-kc-sky">Budget Setup (~$100)</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>Heltec V3 or similar device</span><span class="font-semibold">$25-30</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>10W solar panel</span><span class="font-semibold">$15-20</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>10Ah LiFePO4 battery</span><span class="font-semibold">$20-25</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>Basic outdoor antenna (3-5 dBi)</span><span class="font-semibold">$10-15</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>Weatherproof enclosure</span><span class="font-semibold">$10-15</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>Mounting hardware (pole, clamps, etc.)</span><span class="font-semibold">$15-25</span></div>
          <div class="border-t border-border-light dark:border-border-dark pt-2 mt-3 flex justify-between font-semibold"><span>Total</span><span>$95-130</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-3xl border-2 border-mesh-green/30 bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-mesh-green/20 dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mesh-green">Better Setup (~$150)</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>RAK WisBlock Meshtastic or T-Beam</span><span class="font-semibold">$40-50</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>20W solar panel</span><span class="font-semibold">$25-30</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>10Ah LiFePO4 with better controller</span><span class="font-semibold">$30-40</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>Better outdoor antenna (5-8 dBi)</span><span class="font-semibold">$20-30</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>Quality weatherproof enclosure</span><span class="font-semibold">$15-20</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>Flagpole or better mounting solution</span><span class="font-semibold">$30-50</span></div>
          <div class="border-t border-border-light dark:border-border-dark pt-2 mt-3 flex justify-between font-semibold"><span>Total</span><span>$160-220</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-3xl border-2 border-prairie-gold/30 bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-prairie-gold/20 dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-prairie-gold">Stealth/HOA Setup (~$175)</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>Compact device (RAK or similar)</span><span class="font-semibold">$50-70</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>Small solar panel (10-15W)</span><span class="font-semibold">$20-25</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>Compact battery (10Ah)</span><span class="font-semibold">$25-35</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>Low-profile antenna</span><span class="font-semibold">$15-25</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>Disguise elements (birdhouse, decorative box, etc.)</span><span class="font-semibold">$20-40</span></div>
          <div class="flex justify-between"><span>Specialized mounting for stealth</span><span class="font-semibold">$25-40</span></div>
          <div class="border-t border-border-light dark:border-border-dark pt-2 mt-3 flex justify-between font-semibold"><span>Total</span><span>$155-235</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Testing Process -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Test before you commit</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>Don't build a permanent installation without testing first.</strong> Buy a cheap device ($25-30), test different locations around your property, see what actually works in your specific situation.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 space-y-4">
      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Test 1: Indoor vs outdoor performance</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p>Put the device in your attic or near a window. Check how many nodes you can see and signal strength. Then move it outside. Compare.</p>
          <p>You might be surprised—some buildings work okay indoors. Others attenuate too much and outdoor is required.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Test 2: Elevation difference</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p>Compare ground level vs 6 feet (fence height) vs 10-15 feet (temporary pole). Use a ladder, temporary mast, whatever it takes to test the heights you're considering.</p>
          <p>Track number of nodes seen and SNR (signal-to-noise ratio) for each position.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Test 3: Power consumption measurement</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p>Before buying solar, measure actual power draw of your specific device configured as you plan to run it. Use a USB power meter ($10-15 on Amazon).</p>
          <p>Router mode uses more power than client mode. Measure your actual configuration.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Test 4: Antenna polarization</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p>Vertical polarization is standard. But if your mounting situation makes horizontal easier, test it. You'll lose 3-6 dB, but that might be acceptable trade-off for better mounting or HOA compliance.</p>
          <p>Test both and see if horizontal still reaches nodes you care about.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Maintenance Reality -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Ongoing maintenance</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>Almost none required.</strong> That's the honest truth.
      </p>
      <p>
        Router 1 has been running for months. I've climbed up to check on it exactly twice—once to adjust antenna after a storm, once to clean bird droppings off the solar panel (which probably wasn't even necessary).
      </p>
      <p>
        Check status via the mesh app occasionally. If it stops responding, then go physically check. Otherwise, it just runs.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 rounded-xl bg-kc-blue/5 border border-kc-blue/20 p-5 dark:bg-kc-sky/5 dark:border-kc-sky/20">
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
        <strong>Annual maintenance checklist:</strong> Inspect weatherproof seals, clean solar panel if dirty, check battery voltage, verify firmware is current. That's it. 30 minutes once a year.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Get Started -->
  <section class="mt-12 text-center">
    <div class="inline-block rounded-3xl bg-gradient-to-br from-kc-blue to-kc-red p-8 text-cream-50 shadow-card md:p-10">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold">Stop overthinking, start deploying</h3>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-xl text-base opacity-95">
        Buy a $30 device. Test it in your attic. If that works, great. If not, put it on a 15-foot flagpole with a $20 solar panel. Done.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-4">
        <a
          href="/get-started/join"
          class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-cream-50 px-6 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-kc-blue transition hover:bg-surface-200"
        >
          Quick Start Guide
        </a>
        <a
          href="/get-started/hardware"
          class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-full border border-cream-50 px-6 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-cream-50 transition hover:bg-cream-50 hover:text-kc-blue"
        >
          Hardware Details
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
